In programming, the `static` keyword has different meanings depending on the context. Here are a few common scenarios:

### 1. Static Variables

When used with variables, `static` means that the variable is shared across all instances of a class. It is initialized only once, when the class is loaded, and retains its value between method calls.

```java
public class MyClass {
    public static int count = 0;

    public void increment() {
        count++;
    }
}
```

In this example, `count` is a static variable that can be accessed from any instance of `MyClass`.

### 2. Static Methods

When used with methods, `static` means that the method can be called without creating an instance of the class. It belongs to the class itself, rather than any instance of the class.

```java
public class MyClass {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MyClass.staticMethod();
    }

    public static void staticMethod() {
        System.out.println("Static method called");
    }
}
```

In this example, `staticMethod` is a static method that can be called without creating an instance of `MyClass`.

